    <body.head>
      <hedline>
        <hl1>The bin Laden Tape: Will It Affect the Vote?</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Ann MacRae, whose daughter was killed on Sept 11, disagrees with David Brooks's premise that Sen Kerry is using Sept 11 for political advantage and Pres Bush is not; says Bush continually invokes it in speeches and campaign advertising, and fought creation of investigatory commission and their recommendations (Oct 30 Op-Ed column)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Brooks (''The Osama Litmus Test,'' column, Oct. 30) accuses John Kerry of using Sept. 11 for his own political advantage, while, Mr. Brooks writes, George W. Bush understands the evil of Osama bin Ladin ''so deep in his soul that it consumes him.'' I disagree.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>David Brooks (''The Osama Litmus Test,'' column, Oct. 30) accuses John Kerry of using Sept. 11 for his own political advantage, while, Mr. Brooks writes, George W. Bush understands the evil of Osama bin Ladin ''so deep in his soul that it consumes him.'' I disagree.</p>
        <p>Not only does George Bush continually invoke the tragedy in his speeches and campaign advertising, but Sept. 11 also dominated the Republican convention, beginning with its timing and locale. This qualifies as political use of 9/11.</p>
        <p>George Bush fought the creation of the independent commission to investigate the Sept. 11 attacks and also tried to block its progress.</p>
        <p>If Mr. Bush truly feels the evil ''deep in his gut,'' as Mr. Brooks suggests, he would have made the prevention of future attacks a top priority of his administration by supporting the investigation of the Sept. 11 attacks rather than trying to protect himself politically from the truths the commission sought to find.</p>
        <p>Finally, the carrying out of the commission's recommendations has been stalled by political maneuvering, which could have been avoided if the president were fully committed to protecting America from terrorism.</p>
        <p>Ann MacRae  New York, Oct. 30, 2004</p>
        <p>The writer's daughter, Catherine Fairfax MacRae, was killed on Sept. 11.</p>
      </block>
